<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-25T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-25T12:00:00-05:00" n="257" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d257">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1175</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-25T17:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 25, 1915, 5 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 8 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2159. Your 1603, May 23 [22]. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward
                                    Grey</persName> informs me that the British Government clearly
                                understand that the cotton arrangement is private and unofficial and
                                in no way involves our Government. He will forthwith give to the
                                newspapers here a statement to this effect and he is so telegraphing
                                to <persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1">Spring Rice</persName>.</p>
                            <p>I have exactly followed your instructions given in several telegrams
                                about shipping controversies distinctly to inform the Foreign Office
                                that the representations made must be understood as in no way
                                prejudicial to the American attitude toward the order in council. In
                                conversation also with <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward
                                    Grey</persName> I have a number of times definitely informed him
                                to the same effect. There is therefore no misunderstanding in his
                                mind on this point.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>